      "properties": {
        "name": "Mount Inago",
        "broad_region": "Northern",
        "area_ha": 331.448,
        "trigger_groups": "Herpetofauna, Insects",
        "kba_criteria": "A1a, A1e, B1",
        "threats": [
          "Deforestation for small scale agriculture,",
          "ongoing slash and burn of forest and no regulation,",
          "ogging and",
          "unsustainable hunting"
        ],
        "kba_rationale": "Mount Inago forms part of the sky island conservation corridors of northern Mozambique, together with Chiperone, Namuli, Ribauè-Mpalue and Mabu (Tolley et al., 2017). It is home to several species of plants and animals, with current information suggesting that at least 7 endemic species with restricted distributions occur on the mountain. Of these, there are three reptiles - the Critically Endangered Inago Pygmy Chameleon (Rhampholeon bruessoworum, CR), and two others submitted to the IUCN for further consideration (Lygodactylus inago and Nadziakambia inago). In addition, there is one Endangered amphibian (Nothophryne inagoensis, EN) and three species of insect (Cymothoe baylissi, Alaena lamborni and Neococenyra bioculata) which have been assessed against the IUCN Red List but not yet published. Moreover, there is a potential new freshwater crab (Potamonautes sp.) yet to be described, and at least one cycad (Encephalartos sp.) not matching any currently known species. Because of the seven species triggering KBA status, Inago Mountain is regarded as a KBA.",
        "description": "Mount Inago is in Malema District, in the western section of Nampula Province, northern Mozambique. Malema District is bordered by Zambezia Province to the south and Niassa Province to the north (Bayliss et al., 2010). The geology of Mt Inago, which is mainly granite-porphyrite, is very similar to the Namuli massif due to their close proximity. According to Timberlake et al. (2009), granite-porphyrite encroached the migmatites of the Nampula and Namarroi series around 1100-850 million years ago. The Inago massif elevation ranges from 300-1870 m, with the main peak reaching 1804 m altitude. Rainfall in Malema District averages 1300 mm per annum. The major vegetation surrounding the mountain is miombo woodland, particularly up to 1,000 m. From 1,000 to 1,600 m of altitude, the vegetation is mainly forest, with stream valleys covered by riverine forest. Beyond 1,500 m elevation, grasslands and rocky shrublands are also found.",
        "trigger_species": [
          "Rhampholeon bruessoworum (CR)",
          "Lygodactylus inago (DD)",
          "Nadziakambia inago (DD)",
          "Nothophryne inagoensis (EN)",
          "Cymothoe baylissi (CR)",
          "Alaena lamborni (DD)",
          "Neococenyra bioculata (DD)"
        ],
        "photos": []
      }
