      "properties": {
        "name": "Grande Bazaruto",
        "broad_region": "Southern",
        "area_ha": 5236.358,
        "trigger_groups": "Marine Mammals, Sea Turtles, Plants, Birds, Herpetofauna",
        "kba_criteria": "A1a, A1b, A1c, A1d, B1",
        "threats": [
          "Artisanal fishing,",
          "subsistence and",
          "tinerant agriculture"
        ],
        "kba_rationale": "The Bazaruto Archipelago and San Sebastian peninsula is home to at least eight species (marine and terrestrial) that meet various KBA criteria thresholds, including two reptiles with restricted distribution (Lygosoma lanceolatum, LC; Scelotes insularis, LC), and one threatened reptile (Scelotes duttoni, VU), all of which are endemic to the area. One endangered sea turtle (Chelonia mydas, EN) also occurs at the site, where it is threatened by by-catch, illegal targeting and consumption by the local fishermen (Jacobsen et al., 2010). The Bazaruto Archipelago is also home to what is possibly the only viable population of dugongs (Dugong dugong, VU) in the Western Indian Ocean (Guissamulo, 2004; Pereira & Videira, 2009). The Indian Ocean humpback dolphin (Sousa plumbea, EN) - a species with a narrow habitat preference, restricted distribution and low abundances (Braulik et al., 2015) - also occurs at the site. 75 Damara Terns (Sterna balaenarum, VU) have also been recently recorded at San Sebastian peninsula, most likely representing a local non-breeding population of migrants from southern breeding grounds. This population represents 1.4-3.7% of the global population, making the San Sebastian area globally significant for this species. There are also three endemic plant species found in the site, namely, Jatropha subaequiloba (VU), Memecylon insulare (CR) and Triainolepis sancta (LC).",
        "description": "The Bazaruto Archipelago is made up of 5 islands in the province of Inhambane, and is already designated as a national park. The Bazaruto archipelago was formed from the San Sebastian Peninsula about 7 000 years ago (Everett et al., 2008), and the proposed KBA covers both the archipelago and peninsula. The Peninsula consists of undulating sandy dunes rising from sea level to 96 m a.s.l (Tinley 1985). The freshwater bodies all lie at or near sea level but vary in size and permanence, the largest being up to 1000 ha in extent (van der Walt, pers. comm. cited by Jacobsen et al., 2010). The regional climate is warm and humid, with rainfall ranging from 600-800 mm per annum (Jacobsen et al., 2010). The average temperatures are around 30°C in summer and 18°C in winter, with an average annual temperature of 24°C (Everett et al., 2008). The San Sebastian peninsula is dominated by miombo woodland interspersed with a diversity of habitats that include wetlands, freshwater lakes, tidal mudflats, salt marshes and mangrove swamps. The marine area includes estuaries, a sand peninsula barrier along the seaward boundary of the Inhambane Estuary, islands, and coral reefs (Lambrechts 2001 cited by Peel, 2002).",
        "trigger_species": [
          "Chelonia mydas (EN)",
          "Dugong dugon (VU)",
          "Jatropha subaequiloba (VU)",
          "Memecylon insulare (CR)",
          "Mochlus lanceolatus (LC)",
          "Scelotes duttoni (LC)",
          "Scelotes insularis (LC)",
          "Sousa plumbea (EN)",
          "Sternula balaenarum (VU)",
          "Triainolepis sancta (LC)"
        ],
        "photos": []
      }
