        "kba_rationale": "Despite ongoing challenges, Derre Forest Reserve together with nearby areas still holds exceptional biodiversity. About 670 flora species are likely to occur at this site, including many endemic and near-endemic species to Mozambique. Many fauna species of conservation concern have been recorded, particularly birds such as Acrocephalus griseldis (EN), Ardeola idea (EN), Balearica regulorum (EN), Bucorvus leadbeateri (VU), Gyps africanus (EN), Polemaetus bellicosus (VU), Sagittarius serpentarius (VU) and Trigonoceps occipitalis (CR). The proposed KBA also holds important mammal species such as Lycaon pictus (EN), Hippopotamus amphibius (VU) and Smutsia temminckii (VU). Of the threatened biodiversity elements in Derre Forest Reserve, there are at least two species which are KBA trigger species: Nothobranchius krysanovi (VU), a freshwater fish with a narrow distribution range experiencing ongoing degradation due to human activities (Nagy and Watters, 2019), and Tarenna longipedicellata (VU), a lowland forest plant impacted by expansion of subsistence agriculture, settlement, logging, and excessive burning (Darbyshire et al., 2019).",
        "description": "The Proposed KBA covers an area of about 3901 km², roughly following the boundaries of Derre Forest Reserve in Zambézia province, Central Mozambique. According to the Köppen climate classification, the region is dominated by tropical rainy savannah climate. The average annual temperature is about 23°C, with maximum and minimum averages of 29°C and 17°C, respectively (MAE, 2005). The monthly average rainfall is 1017 mm, with January being the wettest month (MAE, 2005). Geomorphologically, the region is dominated by a plateau with an altitude above 400 m. This site is mostly of alluvial clay soils (MITADER, 2015b) and there are several rivers running through, including Chire, Luala, Luamba, Muelide, Missongue, Thambe, Luó and Bualizo, with the Chire River standing out for its importance (MEF and MITADER, 2015a). In terms of vegetation, the northwest section is dominated by Miombo forests, with mostly deciduous species where Brachystegia spp. and Julbemardia paniculata are dominant. There are also dry forests, woods and acacia scrub, swamps, alluvial zones, sandbanks and riverine forests along the main lines of water (MEF and MITADER, 2015a). The vegetation in the southeast is also quite diverse, with different types of habitats forming more or less continuous patches of vegetation (MEF and MITADER, 2015b).",
        "trigger_species": [
          "Nothobranchius krysanovi (VU)",
          "Tarenna longipedicellata (VU)"
        ],
        "photos": []
